---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ProductShot from '@/components/ProductShot.astro';
import TrialCTA from '@/components/TrialCTA.astro';

const title = 'How Trust Leader works: map, practise, reflect and review';
const description = 'See how Trust Leader turns one working relationship into a Trust Map, focused behaviour practice, private reflection and dated evidence of movement.';
const site = Astro.site || new URL('https://www.thetrustleader.com');
const softwareSchema = {
  '@type': 'SoftwareApplication',
  name: 'Trust Leader',
  applicationCategory: 'BusinessApplication',
  operatingSystem: 'Web',
  url: new URL('/how-it-works/', site).toString(),
  description,
  offers: {
    '@type': 'Offer',
    name: '28-day free trial',
    price: '0',
    priceCurrency: 'GBP'
  }
};
---

<BaseLayout title={`${title} — Trust Leader`} description={description} pageClass="how-page" structuredData={softwareSchema}>
  <header class="page-hero page-hero--product">
    <div class="shell page-hero__grid">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
        <h1>Give the trust conversation somewhere to go.</h1>
        <p class="lede">Map one real relationship, choose one behaviour to practise, reflect privately and review dated evidence together.</p>
        <a class="button button--green" href="#trust-journey">Follow the Trust Journey</a>
      </div>
      <div class="loop-visual" aria-label="Trust Leader process: map, focus, practise, reflect and review">
        <span>Map</span><span>Focus</span><span>Practise</span><span>Reflect</span><span>Review</span>
        <strong>One real relationship</strong>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="proof-strip" aria-label="Trust Leader approach">
    <div class="shell proof-strip__grid proof-strip__grid--three">
      <p>Structure for the trust work. Practice in the relationship. Evidence for the next conversation.</p>
      <div><strong>05</strong><span>Trust Questions</span></div>
      <div><strong>01</strong><span>Behavioural focus</span></div>
      <div><strong>28</strong><span>Days in the trial</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="trust-journey" aria-labelledby="journey-heading">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <div><p class="eyebrow">The Trust Journey</p><h2 id="journey-heading">A connected loop, not a content course.</h2></div>
        <p>The platform gives the work a structure. The important action still happens with the person whose confidence matters.</p>
      </div>

      <ol class="journey-steps">
        <li class="journey-step">
          <div class="journey-step__copy"><span>01 · Identify</span><h3>See where confidence may be held back.</h3><p>Your client chooses one person and one outcome that depends on the relationship. The Trust Map uses five questions to make their current view specific.</p><strong>What this gives you</strong><p>A named relationship, a real goal and one area you can work with.</p></div>
          <ProductShot number="01" label="Trust Map" description="Maya’s view of how Daniel currently experiences Delivery and Consistency." />
        </li>
        <li class="journey-step journey-step--reverse">
          <div class="journey-step__copy"><span>02 · Focus</span><h3>Choose one behaviour that could matter.</h3><p>The largest gap does not become a verdict. It becomes a place to explore. Maya chooses B5 · Flag It Early because Daniel needs earlier updates and fewer surprises.</p><strong>What this gives you</strong><p>A practical choice instead of a broad instruction to “work on trust”.</p></div>
          <ProductShot number="02" label="Choose a behaviour" description="Delivery and Consistency becomes the focus for Maya’s first 28-day journey." align="end" />
        </li>
        <li class="journey-step">
          <div class="journey-step__copy"><span>03 · Design</span><h3>Turn the focus into short practice.</h3><p>Three activities help Maya notice, rehearse and use the behaviour in the real relationship. The work continues between conversations.</p><strong>What this gives you</strong><p>A client who returns with something they tried, not only something they intended.</p></div>
          <ProductShot number="03" label="Behaviour Playlist" description="If Only, Early Warning and Red Flag Slalom form Maya’s fictional demonstration playlist." />
        </li>
        <li class="journey-step journey-step--reverse">
          <div class="journey-step__copy"><span>04 · Facilitate</span><h3>Act where the trust is needed.</h3><p>The activity is a prompt for workplace action, not screen completion. Maya raises a risk while Daniel still has choices.</p><strong>What this gives you</strong><p>A bridge from the coaching or L&D conversation into daily work.</p></div>
          <ProductShot number="04" label="Activity guidance" description="A short prompt prepares Maya to flag a live risk clearly and early." align="end" />
        </li>
        <li class="journey-step">
          <div class="journey-step__copy"><span>05 · Reflect</span><h3>Record what happened privately.</h3><p>Reflections and journals are private by default. Your client can decide what to bring into the next conversation, while the platform keeps a dated record for them.</p><strong>What this gives you</strong><p>Specific material for reflection without turning private thinking into surveillance.</p></div>
          <ProductShot number="05" label="Private reflection" description="Maya records what she tried, what happened and what she noticed." />
        </li>
        <li class="journey-step journey-step--reverse">
          <div class="journey-step__copy"><span>06 · Review</span><h3>Revisit the map and decide what comes next.</h3><p>The same relationship and questions can be reviewed later. Maya’s fictional score moves from 2 to 3. That is early movement in her own view, not proof or a final verdict.</p><strong>What this gives you</strong><p>Dated evidence for a better conversation about progress and the next choice.</p></div>
          <ProductShot number="06" label="Trust Journey review" description="The review connects the starting map, practice, reflections and later score." align="end" />
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--navy">
    <div class="shell measurement-grid">
      <div><p class="eyebrow eyebrow--light">A straight word about measurement</p><h2>A baseline, not a verdict.</h2></div>
      <div><p>The Trust Map records one person’s structured view of how another may experience them. It is not an objective diagnosis of whether they are trusted.</p><p>Its value comes from being specific, dated and repeated under the same questions. That makes movement discussable while leaving room to ask the other person directly.</p></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--green"><div class="shell"><TrialCTA /></div></section>
</BaseLayout>

